                "href": "/profile/Stacie-Taylor-Cornett"
            },
            "answer_text": "Strangely, this is the second time I have had a request to answer a question about mice in a bed\u2014the first time, I thought it was so unusual that it was truly a unique situation; now, I can\u2019t help but wonder what is going on?! Is it becoming a cultural norm to eat in bed? The reason I wonder that is because my experience with wild mice in a home is that they will go to where the food is. So growing up, that meant every once in awhile, we would get a mouse in the kitchen (or the basement, but that\u2019s how they got in). I did have one time where a mouse was seen in my bedroom, but again, it was due to a specific entry point: Mine and my sister\u2019s shared bedroom was situated over the garage. We had recently converted the house from the old radiator system to the new (at that time) floor-board heaters. Unfortunately, when the old radiator was taken out of the bedroom, that left a small, circular hole in the floor where the pipe used to be. Before we got it covered up, we noticed a mouse pop up through the hole, but it scurried back down into the garage as soon as it saw us noticing it. Then we securely covered the hole, no more problem. I suspect that if the mouse had gone undetected, it would have made its way to the kitchen and would not have stayed long in the bedroom. The point is, if you are finding mice in your bedroom at all, it would be because there is an entry point from the outside that they are accessing to get in, and if there is food in the bedroom, that is what they will be drawn to. Unless you have a habit of eating in bed or keeping food next to it, it is doubtful that mice will climb into your bed when you are sleeping. If you have been eating there and have observed mice in the room: remove all food from your bedroom (wash your bedding and vacuum, crumbs are still food to a mouse), and try to find how the mice are getting in so that you can seal off the holes. ",
