            },
            "answer_text": " You open your eyes and the first thing you see is this^. \u201cOh, shucks!\u201d, the mouse thinks. \u201cCaught red-handed. Gotta run!\u201d And before you can do anything about it, your new little furry friend does a ninja back-flip and disappears into the night, leaving you traumatised for life. How likely is this to happen? If we exclude the verbal thought and doing advanced acrobatics segment of the story - more likely than you think. If you have a mouse in your room, then it\u2019s very possible it will crawl in your bed. However, they don\u2019t do it out of sheer malice. Usually, they\u2019re just trying to traverse the distance between their nest and their food source. There\u2019s two things you can do: Make your room inhospitable for mice. Keep it clean. Avoid clutter. Don\u2019t bring food in and the mice will have earthly business there.Get the ultimate bedroom mouse guard. ",
